# AtpClient + KinoAtpClient demo

```elixir
Mix.install([
  {:kino_atp_client, "~> 0.6"}
])
```

## LocalExec: prove a TPTP problem with a local E prover

```elixir
Application.put_env(:atp_client, :local_exec,
  binary: "/home/johannes/.local/bin/eprover",
  args: ["--auto", "--tstp-format", "--cpu-limit=10"],
  cpu_timeout_s: 10
)

problem = """
fof(tautology, conjecture, (p => p)).
"""

AtpClient.LocalExec.query(problem, [])
```

## Isabelle: prove a lemma via the resident server

The container's MCP launcher starts an Isabelle server (`atp`, port 9999)
and writes its password to `/workspace/.isabelle_server_info`. If you
haven't started Claude Code in this container yet, start the server by
hand first: `isabelle server -n atp -p 9999 &` and note the printed
password.

```elixir
password =
  "/workspace/.isabelle_server_info"
  |> File.read!()
  |> String.split("\n", trim: true)
  |> Enum.find_value(fn
    "password=" <> pw -> pw
    _ -> nil
  end)

session = AtpClient.Isabelle.open_session(
  host: "127.0.0.1",
  port: 9999,
  password: password,
  session: "HOL"
)

theory = ~S"""
lemma "P \<or> \<not> P" by auto
"""

AtpClient.Isabelle.prove_theory(session, theory, "Tautology")
```

## Smart cells

With `kino_atp_client` installed, the *"+ Smart"* cell menu offers the
AtpClient smart cells — see the package's own `examples/demo.livemd` in
`jcschuster/KinoAtpClient` for the full tour.

<!-- livebook:{"attrs":"eyJiYWNrZW5kIjoic290cHRwIiwicHJvYmxlbV9zdHIiOiJ0aGYodGVzdCwgY29uamVjdHVyZSwgJHRydWUgPT4gJHRydWUpLiIsInByb29mX21ldGhvZCI6ImJ5IGF1dG8iLCJzeXN0ZW0iOiJMZW8tSUlJLS0tMS44LjAiLCJ0aGVtZSI6IkRyYWN1bGEiLCJ0aW1lX2xpbWl0Ijo1LCJ0cHRwNHhfZW5hYmxlZCI6ZmFsc2V9","chunks":null,"kind":"Elixir.KinoAtpClient.AtpSolver","livebook_object":"smart_cell"} -->

```elixir
# Generated by ATP Solver (backend: SystemOnTPTP)
problem = "thf(test, conjecture, $true => $true)."
system = "Leo-III---1.8.0"
time_limit = 5

case AtpClient.SystemOnTptp.query_system(problem, system, time_limit_sec: time_limit, raw: true) do
  {:ok, output} ->
    IO.puts(output)
    output

  {:error, reason} ->
    raise "SystemOnTPTP error: #{inspect(reason)}"
end

```

